edu.uidaho.junicon.runtime.junicon.iterators

Class IconOperation<T>

  • java.lang.Object
    • edu.uidaho.junicon.runtime.junicon.iterators.IconIterator<T>
      • edu.uidaho.junicon.runtime.junicon.iterators.IconComposition<T>
        • edu.uidaho.junicon.runtime.junicon.iterators.IconOperation<T>
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    IIconComposition<T>, IIconIterator<T>, Iterable<T>, Runnable, Callable<T>, Iterator<T>

    public class IconOperation<T>
extends IconComposition<T>
    IconOperation maps an operator over the product of its operands, and lifts the result to an IconAtom. All operators and control constructs take generators as operands, and effect a similar map over cross-product, equivalent to a monad bind.

    IconOperation is implemented using IconProduct which has a built-in map. The operator is passed as a closure that performs the operation, for example x+y, on primitive data types. For example: 

            I+J => IconProduct(I,J).map((x,y)->x+y) = (x in I) & (y in J) & !(x+y)
    The operator can be set to return a boolean using setIsBoolean(), in which case the iterator fails if the result is false.

    IconOperation is variadic, in that it can accept any number of operands. Assign, however, only has two operands, since it is right associative and the grammar recurses for right associative rules.

    The assignment operator can be augmented, e.g., x += y 

            new IconAssign().augment(IconOperator.binary(op))
    Can curry into a static factory for a given operator, for ease of use. USAGE: static plus = IconOperation.curryOver({x,y -> x+y}).getCurry() plus.over(x,y)
